{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011dVkNoYbCNwL2ozhAMzvL2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have enough information to provide a thorough analysis. Here is my report.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-Iteration Contradiction Analysis: Iteration 26 vs. Prior Iterations\n\n### CONTRADICTION 1: Section-Label Merge Blocking Relaxation (Fix 2) vs. Iteration 18 and 22\n\n**What iteration 26 proposes:**\n\nFix 2 relaxes the section-label merge block in the caps-coalescing loop. When a short ALL_CAPS fragment (2-4 words) precedes a single-word section label like `VEGETABLES`, iteration 26 wants to allow the merge:\n\n```typescript\n!isSectionLabel(next.text) ||\n(wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4)\n```\n\n**What earlier iterations did:**\n\n- **Iteration 18** (Change 1) explicitly added `\"warzywa\"` (vegetables) and a large set of Polish food-category labels to `SECTION_LABELS`. The stated rationale was: \"These category labels appear as ALL_CAPS single words at page boundaries. They are never recipe titles.\" The plan called these \"unambiguously structural\" and rated the risk as \"extremely low.\"\n\n- **Iteration 22** (Change 2) further expanded `SECTION_LABELS` with English food category headers including `\"vegetables\"`, `\"seafood\"`, `\"fish\"`, `\"soups\"`, `\"salads\"`, `\"desserts\"` and others. The rationale was that standalone single-word category names like `VEGETABLES`, `FISH & SEAFOOD` were being incorrectly selected as titles.\n\n- **Iteration 22** (Change 5) already recognized this tension and proposed removing `\"placki\"` from `SECTION_LABELS` because it commonly starts recipe titles like `Placki Ziemniaczane`. The current code at line 159 confirms this was done: `// \"placki\" removed -- it commonly starts recipe titles`.\n\n**Are they in tension?**\n\nYes, this is a genuine contradiction. Iterations 18 and 22 added `\"vegetables\"` to `SECTION_LABELS` specifically to prevent standalone `VEGETABLES` from winning as a title. Iteration 26 now wants to bypass that protection when `VEGETABLES` follows a short ALL_CAPS fragment. The risk is that a real page with a category header `VEGETABLES` appearing right after a short ALL_CAPS artifact (e.g., an OCR fragment like `LEMON HERB`) could produce a spurious merge `LEMON HERB VEGETABLES` where `VEGETABLES` was never part of the title.\n\nHowever, the guard conditions (preceding text must be 2-4 words, next must be exactly 1 word) are reasonably narrow. The `\"placki\"` removal precedent from iteration 22 shows the project already acknowledges that category words can legitimately start or complete recipe titles.\n\n**Resolution that handles both cases:**\n\nThe proposed relaxation should additionally check that the preceding fragment looks incomplete -- for example, that it ends with an adjective or preposition rather than a noun. A simpler heuristic: only allow the merge when the preceding fragment has an odd word count or ends with a word that is clearly not a standalone title (e.g., `ROASTED`, `HERB`, `LEMON HERB`). Since this is hard to generalize, a safer approach is: apply the relaxation, but add a **post-merge validation** that checks whether the merged result exists as a phrase elsewhere in the document (similar to iteration 25's corroboration check). If `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` appears as a phrase in the body text, the merge is validated. If not, reject it.\n\nAlternatively, keep the relaxation as proposed but add `\"vegetables\"` to a new `CONDITIONAL_SECTION_LABELS` set that blocks standalone candidates but allows merges -- mirroring the `\"placki\"` approach already established.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 2: `isTitleAbsentPage` Body-Prose Detection (Fix 5) vs. Iteration 23 Fallback Philosophy\n\n**What iteration 26 proposes:**\n\nFix 5 expands `isTitleAbsentPage` to detect body prose (lowercase-starting lines with 4+ words) in addition to ingredients and cooking instructions. It also relaxes `startsWithNumber` to handle Unicode fractions. When `isTitleAbsentPage` fires, the extractor applies a stricter threshold or returns empty.\n\n**What iteration 23 did:**\n\nIteration 23 explicitly added a **last-resort fallback** that returns the first hard-filter-passing candidate when all embedding-based logic produces nothing. The rationale was: \"the system should degrade to a pure heuristic: return the first non-blank line from the candidate pool.\" It also relaxed the `rawScore` threshold for position 0-2 candidates from `> 0.02` to `> -0.05`, specifically to handle cases where embeddings provide no signal for Polish titles.\n\n**Are they in tension?**\n\nPartially. These changes affect different code paths, but they pull in opposite directions philosophically. Iteration 23 made the system more aggressive about returning *something* (trusting hard filters and position), while iteration 26's `isTitleAbsentPage` expansion makes the system more aggressive about returning *nothing* (detecting pages that lack titles).\n\nThe concrete risk: a page that starts with lowercase Polish body prose (e.g., a continuation from a previous page) followed by a legitimate title at position 3+ could trigger `isTitleAbsentPage`, which would then suppress the title. Iteration 23's fallback was specifically designed to handle cases like this -- where the title exists but scores poorly on embeddings.\n\n**Resolution:**\n\nThe two changes can coexist if `isTitleAbsentPage` only fires when ALL of the first 3 non-empty lines are body text (not just 2 of 3), AND the last-resort fallback is allowed to override `isTitleAbsentPage` when it finds a candidate at position 0-2 that passed hard filters. In other words, `isTitleAbsentPage` should be treated as a *hint* that raises the threshold, not as a hard gate that prevents all extraction. Iteration 26's plan does describe it as requiring `rawScore >= 0.10 AND position <= 2`, which is a threshold raise, not a hard block -- so this is likely safe as long as the iteration 23 last-resort fallback still fires for position-0 candidates when `isTitleAbsentPage` is true.\n\nExplicitly verify that the code path is: `isTitleAbsentPage = true` --> require higher threshold --> if nothing passes threshold --> last-resort fallback still runs for position 0-2.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 3: First-After-Preamble Bonus Increase (Fix 4) vs. Iteration 24 Candidate-Relative Position Bonus\n\n**What iteration 26 proposes:**\n\nFix 4 increases the first-after-preamble bonus from +0.08 to +0.12 when the filtered preamble contained a section label or metadata line. It also makes the check more robust by treating blank lines and section labels as \"filtered.\"\n\n**What iteration 24 proposed:**\n\nIteration 24 introduced a **candidate-relative position bonus** -- changing position scoring from raw line position to position among surviving candidates. It also added a \"first candidate after filtered preamble\" bonus of +0.08. These were designed to work together: the candidate-relative position gives the first surviving candidate the maximum position factor, and the +0.08 bonus gives extra weight.\n\n**Are they in tension?**\n\nNot directly contradictory, but there is a stacking risk. If iteration 24's candidate-relative position bonus AND the increased +0.12 first-after-preamble bonus both fire for the same candidate, the combined boost could be excessive. A non-title candidate that happens to be the first one after a filtered preamble (e.g., a short body-text phrase that passes hard filters) would receive both boosts and could beat the actual title at a later position.\n\n**Resolution:**\n\nThis is likely safe in practice because the first surviving candidate after a filtered preamble IS almost always the title. But verify that the two bonuses don't double-count the same positional evidence. If candidate-relative position already gives the first surviving candidate maximum position factor (~+0.12), adding another +0.12 on top means a total of ~+0.24 positional boost, which is quite aggressive. Consider making the first-after-preamble bonus and the candidate-relative position bonus mutually exclusive, or cap their combined effect at +0.15.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 4: Spillover Handling in `findBurstEnd` (Fix 3) vs. Iteration 22 and 25\n\n**What iteration 26 proposes:**\n\nFix 3 says that `CORRUPTED SPILLOVER` should be added to `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` and that `findBurstEnd` should skip further past spillover content -- until 2+ consecutive blank lines, a separator, or an ALL_CAPS line.\n\n**What the current code already has:**\n\nThe current code at line 400 already includes `SPILLOVER` in `OVERFLOW_MARKERS`:\n```\n/\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+SECTION)\\b/i\n```\n\nAnd line 374 already filters `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]` in `passesHardFilters`.\n\n**What iteration 25 observed:**\n\nIteration 25 explicitly analyzed the spillover handling and noted: \"findBurstEnd doesn't skip the garbled preamble lines (they're long, not short), so the proposed `i > 0` guard would never fire.\" It recommended a **different approach** for handling long garbled lines, acknowledging that the current `findBurstEnd` is insufficient for this pattern.\n\n**Are they in tension?**\n\nThe contradiction is subtle. `SPILLOVER` is already in `OVERFLOW_MARKERS`, so iteration 26's statement that it needs to be \"added\" is incorrect -- the marker is already matched. The real problem, as iteration 25 identified, is that `findBurstEnd` finds the marker but then fails to skip far enough because it looks for a blank line or separator that may not exist. Iteration 26 proposes skipping until an ALL_CAPS line with 2+ words, which is the right direction but contradicts its own framing (it claims the marker is missing when it isn't).\n\n**Resolution:**\n\nThe marker detection is already in place. What actually needs to change is the post-marker skip logic in `findBurstEnd` -- specifically, extending it to skip past long body-text lines until it finds a structural signal (ALL_CAPS heading, multiple blank lines, or separator). Iteration 26's proposed skip-until-ALL_CAPS-line approach is sound and does not conflict with earlier iterations, but the implementation should not re-add markers that already exist. Focus on the skip-distance logic only.\n\n---\n\n### CONTRADICTION 5: `\"placki\"` Precedent vs. Iteration 26's Section-Label Merge Relaxation Scope\n\n**What iteration 22 did:**\n\nRemoved `\"placki\"` from `SECTION_LABELS` entirely because it commonly starts recipe titles. This was a clean solution: the word was never treated as a section label at all.\n\n**What iteration 26 proposes:**\n\nInstead of removing `\"vegetables\"` from `SECTION_LABELS` (which would re-introduce the iteration 22 Pattern 2 failures where standalone `VEGETABLES` is picked as a title), iteration 26 keeps it in the set but relaxes the merge-blocking rule. This is a fundamentally different strategy from the `\"placki\"` approach.\n\n**Are they in tension?**\n\nNot a direct contradiction, but an inconsistency in approach. The codebase now has two different solutions for the same problem:\n- For `\"placki\"`: removed from `SECTION_LABELS` entirely (iteration 22)\n- For `\"vegetables\"`: kept in `SECTION_LABELS` but merge-blocking relaxed (iteration 26)\n\nThis inconsistency could confuse future maintainers and makes the behavior harder to reason about.\n\n**Resolution:**\n\nEither approach works, but they should be unified. The cleanest resolution would be to introduce a two-tier label system explicitly:\n1. `HARD_SECTION_LABELS` -- always blocked, even in merges (e.g., `\"skladniki\"`, `\"przygotowanie\"`, `\"ingredients\"`)\n2. `SOFT_SECTION_LABELS` -- blocked as standalone candidates, but allowed in merges when following a short fragment (e.g., `\"vegetables\"`, `\"placki\"`, `\"bread\"`)\n\nThen re-add `\"placki\"` to `SOFT_SECTION_LABELS` and put `\"vegetables\"` there too. This makes the distinction explicit rather than relying on a code-level merge-blocking override.\n\n---\n\n### NO CONTRADICTION: OCR Repair Dictionary Expansion (Fix 1)\n\nIteration 26's Fix 1 (adding common English words like `with`, `the`, `dip`, `pie` to the food dictionary) is a pure expansion of iteration 24's dictionary-guided OCR repair mechanism. It does not reverse or weaken any previous change. Iteration 24 introduced the mechanism; iteration 26 fills gaps. This is safe.\n\n### NO CONTRADICTION: Unicode Fraction Detection (Fix 5, partial)\n\nAdding Unicode fraction characters to `startsWithNumber` is a pure bug fix. No previous iteration addressed this. It fills a gap in ingredient detection that has existed since iteration 19 when `startsWithNumber` was introduced. Safe.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Findings\n\n| # | Iteration 26 Proposal | Conflicting Iteration | Severity | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Relax section-label merge block for `VEGETABLES` | Iter 18, 22: added `vegetables` to `SECTION_LABELS` to prevent standalone selection | **Medium** | Genuine tension. Add post-merge validation or introduce two-tier label system. |\n| 2 | Expand `isTitleAbsentPage` with body-prose detection | Iter 23: added last-resort fallback to always return something | **Low-Medium** | Philosophical tension. Verify last-resort fallback still fires for position 0-2 when `isTitleAbsentPage` is true. |\n| 3 | Increase first-after-preamble bonus to +0.12 | Iter 24: introduced candidate-relative position bonus (+0.08 base) | **Low** | Stacking risk. Cap combined positional boost or make bonuses mutually exclusive. |\n| 4 | Add `CORRUPTED SPILLOVER` to overflow markers | Iter 25: noted `SPILLOVER` is already in markers; current code confirms this | **Low** | Factual error in iteration 26's framing, not a logic contradiction. Fix the skip-distance logic, don't re-add existing markers. |\n| 5 | Section-label merge relaxation approach | Iter 22: removed `placki` from labels entirely as alternative approach | **Low** | Inconsistency in strategy. Unify with two-tier label system. |\n\nThe most actionable finding is **Contradiction 1**. The section-label merge relaxation directly undermines the protection that iterations 18 and 22 carefully built. It needs either a validation gate (corroboration-style check on the merged result) or a proper two-tier label architecture to handle both the \"standalone category header\" and \"word completing a fragmented title\" cases cleanly."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a64fe38e2fca802cf (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 72693\ntool_uses: 14\nduration_ms: 113437</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18f2edd5-ecb4-45b8-8e46-36d66db82038","uuid":"c82d1714-48a9-4804-b0dc-44ae53349326","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need you to check for cross-iteration contradictions in improvement plans for a title extraction system. \n\nRead the improvement plans from iterations 20-25 (the most recent before the current iteration 26):\n- tools/title-loop/docs/20-3b20209/improvement-plan.md\n- tools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md\n- tools/title-loop/docs/22-480d364/improvement-plan.md\n- tools/title-loop/docs/23-6e2e2a7/improvement-plan.md\n- tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md\n- tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/improvement-plan.md\n\nThen compare them against the current iteration 26 plan at:\n- tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md\n\nLook for cases where iteration 26 proposes changes that CONTRADICT or REVERSE changes made in earlier iterations. Common patterns:\n1. Changing a heuristic in one direction when a previous iteration changed it the other way\n2. Removing or weakening a rule that was specifically added to fix a known failure\n3. Adjusting thresholds or weights that were tuned in a previous iteration without acknowledgin