{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01F8f7JDJSHZam6KoFFkPyoq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013A4e9xd9vyruVpstvXzK9f","name":"Edit","input":{"replace_all":false,"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md","old_string":"**Root cause detail:** When a file starts with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]`, the\nhard filter in `passesHardFilters` correctly rejects the spillover annotation line.\nBut `findBurstEnd`'s overflow-marker detection (`OVERFLOW_MARKERS`) doesn't include\n`SPILLOVER` as a standalone marker in the actual text — it looks for\n`PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW`, `PREVIOUS PAGE CONTENT`, etc., but the generated files\nuse `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]` which is a different format.\n\nAfter the spillover line is filtered, the remaining text may have the title buried\ndeep (line 10+) or absent entirely. The extractor gives up because no candidate\nemerges near position 0.\n\n**Fix:** Two changes:\n\n1. Add `CORRUPTED SPILLOVER` to `findBurstEnd`'s `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` pattern so the\n   preamble after the marker is properly skipped:\n\n   ```typescript\n   const OVERFLOW_MARKERS = /\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)|\n     CORRUPTED\\s+SPILLOVER|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+SECTION)\\b/i;\n   ```\n\n   Wait — `SPILLOVER` is already in the pattern. The issue might be that the marker\n   is inside `[brackets]` and `findBurstEnd` looks at `lines[k].text` after splitting,\n   where the `[` is part of the text. Let me re-check.\n\n   Actually, looking at `passesHardFilters` line 374: `if (/^\\[CORRUPTED\\s+SPILLOVER/i.test(text.trim())) return false;`\n   This filters the spillover line from candidates. But `findBurstEnd` operates on\n   raw lines, not filtered candidates. The spillover marker line passes the\n   `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` test because `SPILLOVER` matches. BUT: `findBurstEnd` then looks\n   for a separator (blank line or `====`) after the marker. If the text after the\n   spillover marker is body text without a clear separator, `findBurstEnd` may not\n   advance far enough.\n\n   The real fix: after detecting a spillover/overflow marker, skip ALL lines until\n   either (a) a blank line gap of ≥2 consecutive blanks, or (b) an ALL_CAPS line\n   that looks like a title heading (structural signal for the start of a new recipe).\n\n2. In `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, when `findBurstEnd` was able to skip a spillover\n   preamble, relax the position preference — don't penalize candidates at position 10+\n   just because they're far from line 0. The title position after a spillover can be\n   anywhere in the document.\n\n   Specifically: when `burstEnd > 0` and an overflow marker was detected, set the\n   position factor to treat the first post-burst candidate as position 0 for scoring.\n   This is already partially handled by the candidate-relative position bonus, but\n   `findBurstEnd` needs to actually advance past the spillover content for it to work.","new_string":"**Root cause detail:** When a file starts with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]`, the\nhard filter in `passesHardFilters` correctly rejects the spillover annotation line.\nThe `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex already includes `SPILLOVER` as a match, so\n`findBurstEnd` detects the marker. However, after detecting the marker, `findBurstEnd`\nlooks for a separator (blank line or `====`) to determine where the preamble ends.\nIf the spillover content continues as body text without a clear separator,\n`findBurstEnd` doesn't advance far enough. The title may be buried at line 10+ or\nabsent entirely, and the extractor gives up because no candidate emerges near the\n(insufficiently advanced) burst end.\n\n**Note (iteration 25 context):** Iteration 25 analyzed this same pattern and noted\nthat `findBurstEnd` \"doesn't skip the garbled preamble lines (they're long, not\nshort), so the proposed `i > 0` guard would never fire.\" The core issue is\nskip-distance, not marker detection.\n\n**Fix:** Two changes:\n\n1. Improve `findBurstEnd`'s post-marker skip logic. After detecting an overflow\n   marker (including `SPILLOVER`), skip ALL subsequent lines until either:\n   (a) a gap of ≥2 consecutive blank lines,\n   (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with ≥2 words (structural signal for a new recipe heading).\n\n   This replaces the current \"look for next blank line\" logic which fails when\n   spillover body text continues without separators.\n\n2. In `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, when `findBurstEnd` was able to skip a spillover\n   preamble, relax the position preference — don't penalize candidates at position 10+\n   just because they're far from line 0. The title position after a spillover can be\n   anywhere in the document.\n\n   Specifically: when `burstEnd > 0` and an overflow marker was detected, set the\n   position factor to treat the first post-burst candidate as position 0 for scoring.\n   This is already partially handled by the candidate-relative position bonus, but\n   `findBurstEnd` needs to actually advance past the spillover content for it to work."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1072,"cache_read_input_tokens":40265,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1072},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18f2edd5-ecb4-45b8-8e46-36d66db82038","uuid":"2c99c0bc-0cef-456a-b01b-fb85ae48ab6a"}
